      "id": "582c274cd318a914",
      "text": "The starting point of every learning process in German lessons is the careful perception of a section of the world, the scope of which can be narrower or wider in view of the respective situation. This begins with the planning of the lesson; the teacher must first go through this process alone, with its possible extensions already in mind. Then the teacher goes through the process together with the students. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "553a61368693ab34",
      "text": "[[Perception]] is a dialogical relationship process that basically concerns all \"[[actors]]\" equally – all are entitled to attention. Perception means to get in touch with the world, to enter into a relationship with the subject matter, to allow resonances. However, this also means that the process of perception changes as soon as further actors (the students), their ideas, their previous knowledge and their attitudes are included in this process. Thus, teaching can only be planned up to a certain point.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1d8d63026260cc01",
      "text": "[[Resonance]] is not to be confused with a \"motivation phase\" at the beginning of a learning process, which has to be skipped as quickly as possible by steering the teacher. The valid demands of the world, the students, the teachers and the symbol systems are in principle capable of resonance.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "274bbb242c0958bd",
      "text": "This applies, for example, to the learning area \"writing texts\", still independent of the function of the text to be written: If I want to describe something, the object to be described in its claims and localizations is the starting point of any further work. In the learning area of language observation, a linguistic phenomenon becomes visible, for example, as a perceptible claim to form as well as a means of design; in the learning area of reading, a text is opened up as a specific access to the \"world\"; and in the area of speaking, the situation into which one speaks is made tangible not only strategically, but also with regard to its possible conditions.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7141c21e9e59dc83",
      "text": "These descriptions suggest: Perceptions can take place on very different levels, but they always go towards a meaning that can only be found through forms of elaboration. In German lessons, language is the most important medium of processing and representation, but there are also many other media, such as visual design, physical forms of expression or acoustic design. It is of great importance not to narrow perceptions prematurely, as it often happens in the context of school through various specifications such as curriculum, test formats, didactic considerations – especially untested as so called \"didactic reduction\". Perception can neither be described purely subjectively-emotionally nor purely cognitively or norm-guided. In the minds of the perceivers, the section of the world is confronted with their own construct of what is perceived. Therefore, holistic perceptions, which are initially fleeting, have to be […]\n"
